1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,043
Chapter four. First models.

2
00:00:04,043 --> 00:00:08,087
In this lesson, we will treat the first model as a
professional instrument, not a warm-up exercise.

3
00:00:08,087 --> 00:00:12,130
A beginner often asks, what model should I use?

4
00:00:12,130 --> 00:00:16,173
A professional asks a sharper question: what have I
learned from the simplest model that could possibly work?

5
00:00:16,173 --> 00:00:20,217
That first model gives us a reference point.

6
00:00:20,217 --> 00:00:24,260
Without it, we cannot honestly say what complexity is
buying.

7
00:00:24,260 --> 00:00:28,641
Here is the professional question. Not, can we train a
powerful model.

8
00:00:28,641 --> 00:00:33,023
The question is, what decision improves because this model
exists?

9
00:00:33,023 --> 00:00:37,404
A first model gives the team a measurement baseline. It
also gives the team a shared language.

10
00:00:37,404 --> 00:00:41,786
Product can ask whether the prediction changes the
customer experience.

11
00:00:41,786 --> 00:00:46,167
Operations can ask whether the prediction changes
intervention timing.

12
00:00:46,167 --> 00:00:50,549
Engineering can ask whether the improvement is worth the
serving cost.

13
00:00:50,549 --> 00:00:54,930
That is how model choice moves from taste into evidence.

14
00:00:54,930 --> 00:00:59,347
This lesson is baseline discipline.

15
00:00:59,347 --> 00:01:03,764
A naive baseline shows what happens when we barely model
anything.

16
00:01:03,764 --> 00:01:08,181
An interpretable baseline lets the data speak through a
simple structure.

17
00:01:08,181 --> 00:01:12,599
A richer model comes later, only after the simple model
reveals what it can and cannot explain.

18
00:01:12,599 --> 00:01:17,016
This ladder is important because each step earns the next.

19
00:01:17,016 --> 00:01:21,433
If a linear model already solves the business problem, a
neural network may add cost without adding value.

20
00:01:21,433 --> 00:01:25,850
If the simple model fails in clear ways, those failures
tell us what to try next.

21
00:01:25,850 --> 00:01:30,591
Our case is delivery-time prediction. At dispatch time, we
estimate when the order will arrive.

22
00:01:30,591 --> 00:01:35,333
That supports customer communication and late-delivery
intervention.

23
00:01:35,333 --> 00:01:40,074
This is important because the model is not just predicting
a number.

24
00:01:40,074 --> 00:01:44,816
It is shaping expectations, staffing decisions, and
escalation workflows.

25
00:01:44,816 --> 00:01:49,557
If the estimate is too optimistic, customers become
frustrated.

26
00:01:49,557 --> 00:01:54,299
If it is too pessimistic, the business may over-correct
and waste operational attention.

27
00:01:54,299 --> 00:01:59,040
So even in a small example, the prediction sits inside a
real decision loop.

28
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:04,032
The prediction moment matters.

29
00:02:04,032 --> 00:02:09,023
At dispatch time, the model may know distance, preparation
time, courier load, weather, and rush hour.

30
00:02:09,023 --> 00:02:14,015
It may not know anything that happens after delivery.

31
00:02:14,015 --> 00:02:19,007
This single boundary prevents many accidental leakage
problems.

32
00:02:19,007 --> 00:02:23,998
For example, if we accidentally include the actual arrival
delay, or a support ticket created after the delivery, the
model may look amazing offline and fail in production.

33
00:02:23,998 --> 00:02:28,990
A first model should make this boundary explicit before
training starts.

34
00:02:28,990 --> 00:02:34,108
The dataset is intentionally small and inspectable. Each
row is a past delivery.

35
00:02:34,108 --> 00:02:39,227
The target is total delivery minutes. The features are
simple operational signals.

36
00:02:39,227 --> 00:02:44,345
This is a good first-model setup because a learner can
reason about every input.

37
00:02:44,345 --> 00:02:49,463
Distance should usually increase time. Bad weather should
usually increase time.

38
00:02:49,463 --> 00:02:54,582
Rush hour should usually increase time.

39
00:02:54,582 --> 00:02:59,700
When a feature has an unexpected direction, that does not
automatically mean the model is wrong, but it gives us a
concrete question to investigate.

40
00:02:59,700 --> 00:03:05,020
Before training, we ask three leakage questions. Would
this feature be known at prediction time?

41
00:03:05,020 --> 00:03:10,340
Was the label created after the outcome? Did train and
test share future information?

42
00:03:10,340 --> 00:03:15,660
A simple first model makes suspicious results easier to
notice.

43
00:03:15,660 --> 00:03:20,980
If the first model is unbelievably accurate, we should not
celebrate immediately.

44
00:03:20,980 --> 00:03:26,300
We should ask whether the data split, timestamp logic, or
feature pipeline accidentally gave the model information
from the future.

45
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:32,015
Now run the local example. The goal is not scale; it is
judgment.

46
00:03:32,015 --> 00:03:37,730
We compare a naive mean baseline with linear regression on
the same delivery-time task.

47
00:03:37,730 --> 00:03:43,445
Both models see the same split and the same metric, so the
comparison is fair.

48
00:03:43,445 --> 00:03:49,160
This is the habit to copy in real work: keep the data,
metric, and evaluation window fixed while the model
changes.

49
00:03:49,160 --> 00:03:53,240
The naive baseline predicts the average delivery time.

50
00:03:53,240 --> 00:03:57,320
It ignores distance, weather, courier load, and rush hour.

51
00:03:57,320 --> 00:04:01,400
That sounds weak, but it answers an essential question.

52
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:05,480
How much error exists before the model learns any
structure?

53
00:04:05,480 --> 00:04:09,560
This number protects us from self-deception.

54
00:04:09,560 --> 00:04:13,640
If a fancy model barely beats the average, then the model
may be impressive technically but weak for this decision.

55
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:18,092
Next we train a linear regression baseline.

56
00:04:18,092 --> 00:04:22,543
It is still simple, but now the model can use structure.

57
00:04:22,543 --> 00:04:26,995
It can learn that distance, weather, and rush hour change
expected time.

58
00:04:26,995 --> 00:04:31,447
The value is that performance and explanation remain
inspectable. Training is fast.

59
00:04:31,447 --> 00:04:35,898
Serving is cheap. The coefficients can be read by a human.

60
00:04:35,898 --> 00:04:40,350
For many production problems, that combination is not a
compromise; it is a serious engineering advantage.

61
00:04:40,350 --> 00:04:45,127
Here is the key result. The naive mean baseline has mean
absolute error nine point one two.

62
00:04:45,127 --> 00:04:49,903
Linear regression drops it to one point nine four. That is
not a small cosmetic improvement.

63
00:04:49,903 --> 00:04:54,680
It is evidence that the simple operational features
contain usable structure.

64
00:04:54,680 --> 00:04:59,457
Mean absolute error is easy to explain: on average, how
many minutes are we wrong?

65
00:04:59,457 --> 00:05:04,233
So the improvement is not just a leaderboard number.

66
00:05:04,233 --> 00:05:09,010
It translates into a much tighter estimate for the people
using the system.

67
00:05:09,010 --> 00:05:13,366
We can inspect the learned weights.

68
00:05:13,366 --> 00:05:17,721
Distance, weather severity, and rush hour all push
delivery time upward.

69
00:05:17,721 --> 00:05:22,077
That direction makes operational sense.

70
00:05:22,077 --> 00:05:26,433
The negative preparation-time weight deserves review,
because it may reflect process timing or dataset quirks.

71
00:05:26,433 --> 00:05:30,789
Interpretability helps us find those questions early.

72
00:05:30,789 --> 00:05:35,144
This is why simple models are not only for beginners.

73
00:05:35,144 --> 00:05:39,500
A professional engineer uses them to find bugs,
assumptions, and business questions before the system
becomes harder to understand.

74
00:05:39,500 --> 00:05:45,385
Now use the ML Baseline Builder skill.

75
00:05:45,385 --> 00:05:51,270
It forces us to name the metric, the evidence, and the
next justified escalation.

76
00:05:51,270 --> 00:05:57,155
Instead of saying, the score looks good, we ask what the
score proves, what it does not prove, and whether a richer
model is justified.

77
00:05:57,155 --> 00:06:03,040
For this case, the skill should point out that the linear
baseline is meaningfully better than naive, but it has not
yet proven robustness across restaurants, weather
conditions, or courier-load extremes.

78
00:06:03,040 --> 00:06:07,820
After the first model, do not jump straight to a bigger
model. Check error slices.

79
00:06:07,820 --> 00:06:12,600
Inspect outliers. Test whether predictions are calibrated
enough for decisions.

80
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:17,380
Review leakage again. Only then should we try richer trees
or ensembles.

81
00:06:17,380 --> 00:06:22,160
A decision gate is not a delay tactic.

82
00:06:22,160 --> 00:06:26,940
It is how we avoid spending a week on complexity when the
next useful action is a one-hour data review.

83
00:06:26,940 --> 00:06:32,470
Here are common mistakes. Skipping the naive baseline.
Changing the metric between models.

84
00:06:32,470 --> 00:06:38,000
Celebrating only the aggregate score. Ignoring slice
failures.

85
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:43,530
Explaining results after the model has already been
chosen.

86
00:06:43,530 --> 00:06:49,060
First-model discipline protects us from all five. The
danger is not simplicity.

87
00:06:49,060 --> 00:06:54,590
The danger is unmeasured complexity, where the team cannot
tell whether a larger model improved the decision or
merely made the pipeline harder to reason about.

88
00:06:54,590 --> 00:07:00,898
Your practice task is simple. Choose one prediction
moment. Write one naive baseline.

89
00:07:00,898 --> 00:07:07,206
Train one interpretable baseline. Compare one metric.
Review one failure slice.

90
00:07:07,206 --> 00:07:13,514
Then ask the professional question: what did complexity
buy?

91
00:07:13,514 --> 00:07:19,822
If you can answer that clearly, you are not just running
machine learning code.

92
00:07:19,822 --> 00:07:26,130
You are building engineering judgment that transfers to
fraud detection, recommendation, search, forecasting, and
almost every applied machine learning system.

93
00:07:26,130 --> 00:07:31,738
The goal is not to stay simple forever. The goal is to
know what complexity buys.

94
00:07:31,738 --> 00:07:37,345
A first model should teach you something before a larger
model enters the room.

95
00:07:37,345 --> 00:07:42,952
Keep one sentence from this chapter: complexity should
earn its place.

96
00:07:42,952 --> 00:07:48,560
In the next lessons, that sentence will guide how we
evaluate models, diagnose failures, and decide when a more
powerful method is truly worth it.
